## Reflection

Problem Set 4 was the most valuable assignment for me because it combined together several core heat transfer ideas into one workflow. In Problem 1, I had to build a thermal resistance network for a photovoltaic panel, account for conduction through multiple layers, include contact resistance, and combine convection and radiation at the exposed surface. That helped me better understand how to translate a physical system into a solvable thermal model and how energy balances connect temperature dependent performance to heat flow. In Problems 2 and 3, I improved my understanding of fin analysis by applying fin resistance, fin effectiveness, and fin efficiency to real design constraints rather than treating them as abstract formulas. What made this assignment especially useful was that it required more than just calculation, it required engineering judgment. I had to choose assumptions carefully, interpret what insulated boundaries and convection-tip conditions meant physically, and decide how to use exact relations, resistance networks, and fin approximations. Going forward, I expect this assignment to be useful because it mirrors the kind of thermal reasoning used in engineering practice.---

